etymologies: mid 16th century: probably a contraction of late Middle English frumple ‘wrinkle’, from Middle Dutch verrompelen. The word originally denoted a mocking speech or action; later (in the plural) ill humor, the sulks; hence a bad-tempered, (later) dowdy woman (early 19th century)

definitions: an unattractive woman who wears dowdy old-fashioned clothes.
shortDefinitions: unattractive woman who wears dowdy old-fashioned clothes
